==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Chromatin
<hw>Chro"ma*tin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld>
<def>The deeply staining substance of the nucleus and chromosomes of
eukaryotic cells, composed of DNA and basic proteins (such as histones),
the DNA of which comprises the predominant physical basis of
inheritance. It was, at the beginning of the 20th century, supposed to
be the same substance as was then termed <altname>idioplasm</altname> or
<altname>germ plasm</altname>. In most eukaryotic cells, there is also
DNA in certain plasmids, such as mitochondria, or (in plant cells)
chloroplasts; but with the exception of these cytoplasmic genetic
factors, the nuclear DNA of the <ex>chromatin</ex> is believed to
contain all the genetic information required to code for the development
of an adult organism. In the interphase nucleus the chromosomes are
dispersed, but during cell division or meiosis they are condensed into
the individually recognizable chromosomes. The set of chromosomes, or a
photographic representation of the full set of chromosomes of a cell
(often ordered for presentation) is called a
<partof>karyotype</partof>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Chromatism</ent>⟦br⟧
